<h2>
    Best Rivers for Fishing Near Bend, Oregon
</h2>
<h3>
    Deschutes River (Upper &amp; Lower)
</h3>
<p>
    The <strong>Upper Deschutes</strong> offers gentle water and easy wading for beginners. The <strong>Lower Deschutes</strong>, accessed via Maupin, is legendary for <strong>wild redband trout</strong>, summer steelhead, and incredible hatches.
</p>
<h3>
    Fall River
</h3>
<p>
    A <strong>spring-fed creek</strong> perfect for dry fly and Euro nymphing. It’s fly-only, with catch-and-release rules. Fish are spooky but rewarding.
</p>
<h3>
    Crooked River
</h3>
<p>
    Located below the Bowman Dam, this tailwater fishery stays fishable year-round. Great for numbers of rainbow trout and whitefish—best accessed near Prineville.
</p>
<h3>
    Metolius River
</h3>
<p>
    A technical but gorgeous stream full of wild rainbow trout and the occasional bull trout. Best for experienced fly anglers.
</p>
<h2>
    Best Lakes for Fishing Near Bend
</h2>
<h3>
    Crane Prairie Reservoir
</h3>
<p>
    Trophy <strong>rainbow trout (“cranebows”)</strong>, largemouth bass, and black crappie abound. Shallow, weedy areas are hotspots—fish early or late.
</p>
<h3>
    Wickiup Reservoir
</h3>
<p>
    Home to large <strong>brown trout</strong>, <strong>kokanee</strong>, and occasional trophy rainbows. Fish deeper waters and troll spoons or dodgers with corn for kokanee.
</p>
<h3>
    East Lake &amp; Paulina Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Located in the Newberry Crater, these lakes are stocked with rainbows and kokanee, plus hold wild browns. Dry flies, trolling, and jigging all work well.
</p>
<h3>
   Hosmer Lake
</h3>
<p>
    Fly-fishing only and catch-and-release. Clear water, stunning views, and hungry brookies and rainbows make this an alpine favorite.
</p>
